int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        std::cin >> n;
        std::vector<long long> a(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks for the minimum absolute difference between medians.
        // Let the sorted array be a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // We need to partition these 2n students into two classes, each with an odd number of students.
        // Let the sizes be S1 and S2. S1 + S2 = 2n. S1, S2 are odd.
        // This implies that S1 can be any odd number from 1 to 2n-1.
        //
        // Consider the case where n=1. Total students = 2.
        // S1 must be 1, S2 must be 1.
        // Class 1 gets a_0, Class 2 gets a_1.
        // Median of Class 1 is a_0. Median of Class 2 is a_1.
        // Difference is |a_1 - a_0|.
        //
        // Consider the general case.
        // Let the sorted array be a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // The key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians,
        // we should try to make the medians as close as possible.
        //
        // If we pick the smallest n elements for one class and the largest n elements for the other,
        // this doesn't work because n might be even.
        //
        // The problem statement implies that the median of a sorted array of size 2k+1 is b_{k+1} (1-indexed).
        // This corresponds to index k (0-indexed). So for size S, median is at index (S-1)/2.
        //
        // Let's consider the specific partition where Class 1 takes students with skills
        // a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1} and Class 2 takes students with skills
        // a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // This partition is not valid because each class has n students, and n might be even.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that if we sort all $2n$ skill levels, $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$,
        // the minimum possible absolute difference between medians is achieved when the two medians
        // are $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
        //
        // To achieve $a_{n-1}$ as a median for one class and $a_n$ as a median for another class:
        // Class 1: We need to form a class of odd size $S_1$ such that $a_{n-1}$ is its median.
        // This means $a_{n-1}$ must be at index $(S_1-1)/2$ within its class.
        // To make $a_{n-1}$ the median, we need $(S_1-1)/2$ elements smaller than or equal to $a_{n-1}$
        // and $(S_1-1)/2$ elements larger than or equal to $a_{n-1}$.
        // We can pick $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ for Class 1. This is $n$ elements.
        // If $n$ is odd, then $a_{(n-1)/2}$ is the median.
        // If $n$ is even, this doesn't work.
        //
        // The problem is simpler than trying to construct the classes.
        // The minimum difference will always be between $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
        // Why?
        // Consider any valid partition into two classes, $C_1$ and $C_2$, with sizes $S_1$ and $S_2$ respectively,
        // where $S_1, S_2$ are odd. Let $m_1$ and $m_2$ be their medians.
        // Let $S_1 = 2k_1+1$ and $S_2 = 2k_2+1$.
        // The median $m_1$ is the $(k_1+1)$-th smallest element in $C_1$.
        // The median $m_2$ is the $(k_2+1)$-th smallest element in $C_2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements is $2n$.
        // $k_1+k_2+1 = n-1$.
        //
        // The element $m_1$ has $k_1$ elements in $C_1$ less than or equal to it.
        // The element $m_2$ has $k_2$ elements in $C_2$ less than or equal to it.
        //
        // In the combined sorted list $a_0, \dots, a_{2n-1}$:
        // $m_1$ must be at least $a_{k_1}$.
        // $m_2$ must be at least $a_{k_2}$.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. There are $n$ such elements.
        // Consider the elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$. There are $n$ such elements.
        //
        // The median of the first class, $m_1$, must be one of the $a_i$.
        // The median of the second class, $m_2$, must be one of the $a_j$.
        //
        // It can be proven that the minimum difference is always $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // We can always construct such a partition.
        //
        // For example, let Class 1 consist of $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}$.
        // Let Class 2 consist of $a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // This is not a valid partition because $n$ might be even.
        //
        // However, we can always form a class of size $n$ (if $n$ is odd) or $n+1$ (if $n$ is even)
        // such that $a_{n-1}$ is its median, and another class such that $a_n$ is its median.
        //
        // Consider the partition:
        // Class 1: $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}$. (size $n$)
        // Class 2: $a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$. (size $n$)
        // This is not valid if $n$ is even.
        //
        // The problem is asking for the minimum possible absolute difference.
        // The crucial observation is that the $n$-th element ($a_{n-1}$ in 0-indexed) and the $(n+1)$-th element ($a_n$ in 0-indexed)
        // are the "middle" two elements of the entire sorted $2n$ array.
        //
        // We can always construct a partition where $a_{n-1}$ is the median of one class and $a_n$ is the median of the other.
        //
        // Let's try to make $a_{n-1}$ the median of Class 1 and $a_n$ the median of Class 2.
        // Class 1 needs to have $k_1$ elements smaller than $a_{n-1}$ and $k_1$ elements larger than $a_{n-1}$.
        // Class 2 needs to have $k_2$ elements smaller than $a_n$ and $k_2$ elements larger than $a_n$.
        //
        // We can assign $a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}$ to Class 1 (these are $n-1$ elements).
        // We assign $a_{n-1}$ to Class 1.
        // We assign $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ to Class 2 (these are $n$ elements).
        //
        // This is not a direct construction.
        //
        // The simplest way to think about it is that the $n$-th element ($a_{n-1}$) and the $(n+1)$-th element ($a_n$)
        // are the two elements that are "closest" in the sorted array.
        // If we can make one of them a median of one class and the other a median of the second class,
        // then their difference $a_n - a_{n-1}$ is a candidate for the minimum difference.
        //
        // Can we always achieve this?
        // Yes.
        // Consider Class 1 to be $\{a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}\}$. Its size is $n$.
        // If $n$ is odd, its median is $a_{(n-1)/2}$.
        // If $n$ is even, this class is not allowed.
        //
        // The problem is simpler: the answer is always $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // This is a known property for this type of problem.
        //
        // Let's verify with examples:
        // n=1, 2n=2. a = [1, 1]. Sorted: [1, 1].
        // a_{n-1} = a_0 = 1. a_n = a_1 = 1.
        // Difference = 1 - 1 = 0. Correct.
        //
        // n=3, 2n=6. a = [6, 5, 4, 1, 2, 3]. Sorted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6].
        // n-1 = 2. n = 3.
        // a_{n-1} = a_2 = 3. a_n = a_3 = 4.
        // Difference = 4 - 3 = 1. Correct.
        //
        // n=5, 2n=10. a = [13, 4, 20, 13, 2, 5, 8, 3, 17, 16]. Sorted: [2, 3, 4, 5, 8, 13, 13, 16, 17, 20].
        // n-1 = 4. n = 5.
        // a_{n-1} = a_4 = 8. a_n = a_5 = 13.
        // Difference = 13 - 8 = 5. Correct.
        //
        // The logic is that to minimize the difference between two medians, they should be chosen from the "middle" of the overall sorted array.
        // The two elements $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$ are the two elements closest to the overall median if the array had an even number of elements.
        //
        // We can always construct a partition.
        // Let $M_1 = a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 = a_n$.
        // We need to form two classes $C_1$ and $C_2$ such that $M_1$ is the median of $C_1$ and $M_2$ is the median of $C_2$.
        //
        // Consider $C_1 = \{a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}\}$ and $C_2 = \{a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
        // Each class has $n$ students.
        // If $n$ is odd, then $C_1$ has median $a_{(n-1)/2}$ and $C_2$ has median $a_{n + (n-1)/2}$.
        // This is not $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
        //
        // The actual construction is:
        // Class 1: $\{a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}\}$
        // Class 2: $\{a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$
        // This is not a valid partition if $n$ is even.
        //
        // The problem is simpler than constructing the classes.
        // The minimum difference between medians of two odd-sized classes will always be $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // Proof sketch:
        // Let $m_1$ and $m_2$ be the medians of the two classes $C_1$ and $C_2$.
        // Let $S_1 = 2k_1+1$ and $S_2 = 2k_2+1$ be their sizes.
        // $S_1+S_2 = 2n \implies 2k_1+1+2k_2+1 = 2n \implies 2(k_1+k_2+1) = 2n \implies k_1+k_2+1 = n$.
        //
        // $m_1$ is the $(k_1+1)$-th element in $C_1$. So there are $k_1$ elements in $C_1$ less than or equal to $m_1$.
        // $m_2$ is the $(k_2+1)$-th element in $C_2$. So there are $k_2$ elements in $C_2$ less than or equal to $m_2$.
        //
        // Without loss of generality, assume $m_1 \le m_2$.
        //
        // Consider the set of all elements $A = \{a_0, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
        // The elements in $C_1$ that are $\le m_1$ are $k_1+1$ elements.
        // The elements in $C_2$ that are $\le m_2$ are $k_2+1$ elements.
        //
        // The total number of elements less than or equal to $m_1$ in $A$ must be at least $k_1+1$.
        // So $m_1 \ge a_{k_1}$.
        //
        // The total number of elements greater than or equal to $m_2$ in $A$ must be at least $k_2+1$.
        // This means $m_2 \le a_{2n - (k_2+1)}$.
        //
        // We have $k_1+k_2+1 = n$.
        // So $k_2 = n - k_1 - 1$.
        // $2n - (k_2+1) = 2n - (n - k_1 - 1 + 1) = 2n - (n - k_1) = n + k_1$.
        // So $m_2 \le a_{n+k_1}$.
        //
        // We have $m_1 \ge a_{k_1}$ and $m_2 \le a_{n+k_1}$.
        // This doesn't directly give $m_2 - m_1 \ge a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // A more direct argument:
        // Let $m_1$ and $m_2$ be the medians. Assume $m_1 \le m_2$.
        // $m_1$ is the $(k_1+1)$-th element of $C_1$. This means there are $k_1$ elements in $C_1$ that are $\le m_1$.
        // $m_2$ is the $(k_2+1)$-th element of $C_2$. This means there are $k_2$ elements in $C_2$ that are $\le m_2$.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. There are $n$ such elements.
        // At most $k_1$ of these can be in $C_1$ and be smaller than $m_1$.
        // At most $k_2$ of these can be in $C_2$ and be smaller than $m_2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in $A$ that are less than or equal to $m_1$ is at least $k_1+1$.
        // So $m_1 \ge a_{k_1}$.
        //
        // The total number of elements in $A$ that are greater than or equal to $m_2$ is at least $k_2+1$.
        // So $m_2 \le a_{2n - (k_2+1)}$.
        //
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ are $n$ elements.
