        // Consider the case where we split the array into two halves:
        // Class 1: {a_0, ..., a_{n-1}}
        // Class 2: {a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}}
        //
        // If n is odd, then both classes have size n (odd).
        // The median of Class 1 would be a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // The median of Class 2 would be a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        // The difference would be a_{n + (n-1)/2} - a_{(n-1)/2}.
        //
        // If n is even, this partition is not allowed because class sizes are even.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that to minimize the difference between medians,
        // we should pick the medians from elements that are close to each other in the sorted array.
        //
        // The smallest possible median for any class will be a_0 (if a class has size 1 and contains a_0).
        // The largest possible median for any class will be a_{2n-1} (if a class has size 1 and contains a_{2n-1}).
        //
        // Consider the two "middle" elements in the sorted array: a_{n-1} and a_n.
        //
        // If we can make a_{n-1} the median of one class and a_n the median of another class,
        // then the difference would be a_n - a_{n-1}.
        //
        // Can we always achieve this?
        //
        // Let's try to construct two classes such that a_{n-1} is the median of one and a_n is the median of the other.
        //
        // Class A: {a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1}}
        // Class B: {a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}}
        //
        // Each class has exactly n students.
        // If n is odd, then this is a valid partition.
        // Median of Class A is a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // Median of Class B is a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        // The difference is a_{n + (n-1)/2} - a_{(n-1)/2}.
        //
        // If n is even, this partition is not valid because class sizes are even.
        //
        // The problem asks for the minimum possible absolute difference.
        // The smallest possible difference is 0, which occurs if a_i = a_j for some i, j.
        //
        // Let's consider the specific partition where Class 1 consists of students
        // a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1} and Class 2 consists of students a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // Each class has n students.
        // If n is odd, then this is a valid partition.
        // The median of Class 1 is a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // The median of Class 2 is a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        // The difference is a_{n + (n-1)/2} - a_{(n-1)/2}.
        //
        // What if n is even?
        // We need to make both class sizes odd.
        // The smallest odd size is 1. The largest is 2n-1.
        //
        // Consider the partition where Class 1 has students {a_0, ..., a_{n-1}} and Class 2 has students {a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}}.
        // This is a partition into two groups of size n.
        //
        // The problem statement is a bit tricky. It says "choose one in which the absolute difference ... is minimized".
        // It does not restrict the sizes of the classes beyond being odd.
