        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The first class will have median a[n-1] (0-indexed)
        // The second class will have median a[n] (0-indexed)
        // This corresponds to the elements a_n and a_{n+1} in 1-indexed sorted array.
        // The minimum difference is achieved by taking these two elements as medians.
        // For example, class 1 can be {a_1, ..., a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}} with median a_n
        // and class 2 can be {a_{n+1}} with median a_{n+1}.
        // Or class 1 can be {a_n} with median a_n
        // and class 2 can be {a_1, ..., a_{n-1}, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n}} with median a_{n+1}.
        // In general, we can always construct two classes of odd sizes such that
        // one median is a[n-1] and the other is a[n].
        // For example, Class 1: {a[0], ..., a[n-1]} (size n, if n is odd)
        // Class 2: {a[n], ..., a[2n-1]} (size n, if n is odd)
        // If n is odd, then n-1 is even. The median of a class of size n is a[(n-1)/2].
        // This is not what the problem implies.
        // The problem states that the median of a sorted array b_1, ..., b_{2k+1} is b_{k+1}.
        // For a class of size S = 2k+1, the median is the (k+1)-th element.
        // The smallest possible odd size for a class is 1.
        // If a class has size 1, say {x}, its median is x.
        // If a class has size 3, say {x, y, z} sorted, its median is y.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // We need to pick two elements, say a_i and a_j, to be the medians of the two classes.
        // Let the first class have median M1 and the second class have median M2.
        // To minimize |M1 - M2|, we should pick M1 and M2 to be adjacent in the sorted array.
        //
        // Let's try to make a[n-1] and a[n] the medians.
        // Can we always form two classes of odd sizes such that a[n-1] is the median of one and a[n] is the median of the other?
        // Yes.
        // Class 1: {a[n-1]} (size 1, median a[n-1])
        // Class 2: {a[0], ..., a[n-2], a[n], ..., a[2n-1]} (size 2n-1, median a[n])
        // The size of Class 2 is 2n-1. This is always odd.
        // The elements in Class 2 are sorted. Its median is the ((2n-1)-1)/2 + 1 = n-th element.
        // The elements are a[0], ..., a[n-2], a[n], ..., a[2n-1].
        // The n-th element (1-indexed) in this sequence is a[n].
        // So, we can always achieve |a[n] - a[n-1]|.
        //
        // Is it possible to achieve a smaller difference?
        // Suppose we pick two medians M1 and M2.
        // M1 must be some a_i and M2 must be some a_j.
        // If M1 < M2, then M1 = a_i and M2 = a_j for some i < j.
        // For a_i to be a median of a class of size 2k_1+1, there must be k_1 elements <= a_i and k_1 elements >= a_i.
        // For a_j to be a median of a class of size 2k_2+1, there must be k_2 elements <= a_j and k_2 elements >= a_j.
        //
        // Consider the elements a[n-1] and a[n].
        // Any median M1 must be some a_i. Any median M2 must be some a_j.
        // If we pick a_i and a_j as medians, then we need to partition the remaining $2n-2$ elements.
        //
        // The key insight is that the $n$-th element ($a_{n-1}$ in 0-indexed) and the $(n+1)$-th element ($a_n$ in 0-indexed)
        // are the "most central" elements in the entire sorted array.
        // If we pick any $a_i$ as a median for one class, and $a_j$ as a median for the other,
        // and $i < n-1$ and $j > n$, then $a_j - a_i$ will be at least $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // If $i < n-1$ and $j = n-1$, then $a_{n-1} - a_i$ could be smaller, but then we'd need to find another median.
        //
        // The problem is equivalent to finding two indices $i$ and $j$ such that $a_i$ and $a_j$ can be medians of two classes,
        // and $|a_i - a_j|$ is minimized.
        //
        // Let $S_1$ and $S_2$ be the sizes of the two classes. $S_1 = 2k_1+1$, $S_2 = 2k_2+1$.
        // $S_1+S_2 = 2n$.
        // The median of $S_1$ elements is the $(k_1+1)$-th element.
        // The median of $S_2$ elements is the $(k_2+1)$-th element.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // The element $a_{n-1}$ is the $n$-th element.
        // The element $a_n$ is the $(n+1)$-th element.
        //
        // If we choose $a_{n-1}$ as the median of Class 1, and $a_n$ as the median of Class 2.
        // Class 1: $\{a_{n-1}\}$ (size 1, $k_1=0$, median $a_{n-1}$)
        // Class 2: $\{a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$ (size $2n-1$, $k_2=n-1$, median $a_n$)
        // This is a valid partition. The difference is $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // Can we do better?
        // Suppose we have medians $M_1$ and $M_2$.
        // Let $M_1 = a_i$ and $M_2 = a_j$. Assume $i < j$.
        // For $a_i$ to be a median of a class of size $2k_1+1$, there must be at least $k_1$ elements $\le a_i$ and $k_1$ elements $\ge a_i$.
        // For $a_j$ to be a median of a class of size $2k_2+1$, there must be at least $k_2$ elements $\le a_j$ and $k_2$ elements $\ge a_j$.
        //
        // The total number of elements is $2n$.
        // The total number of elements strictly less than $a_i$ is at most $i$.
        // The total number of elements strictly greater than $a_j$ is at most $2n-1-j$.
        //
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ are the first $n$ elements.
        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are the last $n$ elements.
        //
        // If we pick $a_i$ as median for class 1 and $a_j$ as median for class 2.
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{i-1}$ must be distributed.
        // The elements $a_{i+1}, \dots, a_{j-1}$ must be distributed.
        // The elements $a_{j+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ must be distributed.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that the median of a set of $2k+1$ elements is the $(k+1)$-th element in sorted order.
        // This means there are $k$ elements less than or equal to it, and $k$ elements greater than or equal to it.
        //
        // Let $M_1$ be the median of Class 1, and $M_2$ be the median of Class 2.
        // Let $M_1 = a_x$ and $M_2 = a_y$ for some indices $x, y$.
        // Without loss of generality, assume $x < y$.
        //
        // For $a_x$ to be a median of a class of size $2k_1+1$, it must have $k_1$ elements $\le a_x$ and $k_1$ elements $\ge a_x$.
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{x-1}$ are available to be $\le a_x$.
        // The elements $a_{x+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are available to be $\ge a_x$.
        //
        // For $a_y$ to be a median of a class of size $2k_2+1$, it must have $k_2$ elements $\le a_y$ and $k_2$ elements $\ge a_y$.
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{y-1}$ are available to be $\le a_y$.
        // The elements $a_{y+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are available to be $\ge a_y$.
        //
        // The total number of elements is $2n$.
        // The total number of elements that are $\le a_x$ is $x+1$.
        // The total number of elements that are $\ge a_y$ is $2n-y$.
        //
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{x-1}$ must be assigned to Class 1 or Class 2.
        // The elements $a_{x+1}, \dots, a_{y-1}$ must be assigned to Class 1 or Class 2.
        // The elements $a_{y+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ must be assigned to Class 1 or Class 2.
        //
        // For $a_x$ to be a median, it needs $k_1$ elements from $\{a_0, \dots, a_{x-1}\}$ and $k_1$ elements from $\{a_{x+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
        // For $a_y$ to be a median, it needs $k_2$ elements from $\{a_0, \dots, a_{y-1}\}$ and $k_2$ elements from $\{a_{y+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
        //
        // The total number of elements available for the "less than or equal to" part of $a_x$ is $x$.
        // The total number of elements available for the "greater than or equal to" part of $a_y$ is $2n-1-y$.
        //
        // The minimum number of elements that must be $\le a_x$ in Class 1 is $k_1$.
        // The minimum number of elements that must be $\ge a_y$ in Class 2 is $k_2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements $a_0, \dots, a_{x-1}$ is $x$.
        // The total number of elements $a_{y+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ is $2n-1-y$.
        //
        // The sum of elements in Class 1 is $2k_1+1$.
        // The sum of elements in Class 2 is $2k_2+1$.
        // $(2k_1+1) + (2k_2+1) = 2n \implies 2(k_1+k_2) + 2 = 2n \implies k_1+k_2 = n-1$.
        //
        // The $k_1$ elements smaller than $a_x$ must come from $a_0, \dots, a_{x-1}$ or from elements assigned to Class 1 from $a_{x+1}, \dots, a_{y-1}$.
        // The $k_2$ elements larger than $a_y$ must come from $a_{y+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ or from elements assigned to Class 2 from $a_{x+1}, \dots, a_{y-1}$.
        //
        // The total number of elements $a_0, \dots, a_{x-1}$ is $x$. These can only be $\le a_x$ or $\le a_y$.
        // The total number of elements $a_{y+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ is $2n-1-y$. These can only be $\ge a_x$ or $\ge a_y$.
        //
        // To satisfy the median conditions, we need:
        // $k_1 \le x$ (elements for Class 1 smaller than $a_x$)
        // $k_2 \le 2n-1-y$ (elements for Class 2 larger than $a_y$)
        //
        // Summing these: $k_1+k_2 \le x + (2n-1-y)$.
        // Since $k_1+k_2 = n-1$, we have $n-1 \le x + 2n-1-y$.
        // $n-1 \le x - y + 2n - 1$.
        // $0 \le x - y + n$.
        // $y - x \le n$.
        //
        // This means the distance between the indices of the medians cannot be arbitrarily large.
        //
        // What if $x = n-1$ and $y = n$?
        // Then $y-x = 1$. This satisfies $y-x \le n$.
        //
        // The minimum possible value for $y-x$ is 1 (for distinct medians).
        // If $y-x=1$, then $x=n-1, y=n$.
        // This gives $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // The argument for why $a_n - a_{n-1}$ is minimal:
        // Let $M_1$ and $M_2$ be the medians of the two classes, with $M_1 \le M_2$.
        // Let $C_1$ be the class with median $M_1$ and $C_2$ be the class with median $M_2$.
        // Let $|C_1| = 2k_1+1$ and $|C_2| = 2k_2+1$. We know $k_1+k_2 = n-1$.
        //
        // $M_1$ is the $(k_1+1)$-th element of $C_1$. This means there are at least $k_1$ elements in $C_1$ that are $\le M_1$.
        // $M_2$ is the $(k_2+1)$-th element of $C_2$. This means there are at least $k_2$ elements in $C_2$ that are $\ge M_2$.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. There are $n$ such elements.
        // At most $k_1$ of these can be in $C_1$ and be $\le M_1$.
        // At most $k_2$ of these can be in $C_2$ and be $\le M_2$.
        //
        // All elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ are $\le a_{n-1}$.
        // All elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are $\ge a_n$.
        //
        // The total number of elements that are $\le M_1$ (including $M_1$ itself) is at least $k_1+1$.
        // The total number of elements that are $\ge M_2$ (including $M_2$ itself) is at least $k_2+1$.
        //
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ are $n$ elements.
        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are $n$ elements.
        //
        // If $M_1 < a_{n-1}$, then $M_1$ is one of $a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}$.
        // If $M_2 > a_n$, then $M_2$ is one of $a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        //
        // Suppose $M_1 < a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 > a_n$. Then $M_2 - M_1 > a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // What if $M_1 = a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 = a_n$? We showed this is achievable.
        //
        // What if $M_1 < a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 = a_n$?
        // Then $M_2 - M_1 = a_n - M_1 > a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // What if $M_1 = a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 > a_n$?
        // Then $M_2 - M_1 = M_2 - a_{n-1} > a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // What if $M_1 < a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 < a_n$? This implies $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$.
        // Then $M_1$ and $M_2$ are both from $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$.
        // For $M_2$ to be a median of $C_2$, it needs $k_2$ elements $\ge M_2$.
        // If $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$, then all elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are $\ge M_2$. There are $n$ such elements.
        // So $k_2$ can be at most $n$.
        //
        // This is a standard result for problems involving partitioning into two sets and minimizing difference of medians/sums.
        // After sorting, the optimal medians will always be $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
